:"Lympne, Kent, England"},"en":{"1530–Abt 1625":"1530–about 1625","1530–1625":"1530–1625","1530–Male":"1530–Deceased","1565–1625":"1565–1625","1505–1550":"1505–1550","1505–1593":"1505–1593","1550":"1550","1593":"1593","Abt 1625":"about 1625","13 October 1563":"13 October 1563","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1565":"1565","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1530":"1530","August 1593":"August 1593","1585":"1585","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","1625":"1625","Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, England",", , Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Lympne, Folkestone and Hythe district, Kent, England":"Lympne, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stobaugh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Staubach  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Staubach","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Ernst, Otto.","German: possibly a Swiss German topographic name from Middle High German <i>stouwen</i> ‘to dam’ + <i>bach</i> ‘creek’ or from Bavarian <i>Staub</i> dust' for a ‘waterfall or stream that seems to turn to dust when falling from a high crag’."]}]},{"name":"Ida","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Norman name, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>īd</i> ‘work’. This died out during the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, influenced by its use in  Tennyson's  The Princess (  1847 ) for the central character, who devotes herself to the cause of women's rights and women's education in a thoroughly Victorian way. The name is also associated with Mount Ida in Crete, which was connected in classical times with the worship of Zeus, king of the gods, who was supposed to have been brought up in a cave on the mountainside. In the 1930s it became famous as the name of the film star  Ida Lupino  (  1914–1995 )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ann","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Anne .  In the U.S. <i>Ann</i> is the more frequent spelling."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":19,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":28,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":39,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":55,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":57,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":90,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Ida Ann Stobaugh was born in 1530, in Lympne, Kent, England, her father, Francis Stobaugh, was 25 and her mother, Martha Maddox, was 25. She married Thomas B. Robbins on 13 October 1563, in Lympne, Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died about 1625, in her hometown, at the age of 96."},"et":{"1530–Abt 1625":"1530–umbes 1625","1530–1625":"1530–1625","1530–Male":"1530–Surnud","1565–1625":"1565–1625","1505–1550":"1505–1550","1505–1593":"1505–1593","1550":"1550","1593":"1593","Abt 1625":"umbes 1625","13 October 1563":"13. oktoober 1563","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1565":"1565","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1530":"1530","August 1593":"august 1593","1585":"1585","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","1625":"1625","Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, England",", , Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Lympne, Folkestone and Hythe district, Kent, England":"Lympne, Kent, England"},"fi":{"1530–Abt 1625":"1530–noin 1625","1530–1625":"1530–1625","1530–Male":"1530–Kuollut","1565–1625":"1565–1